{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532153"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:23:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14653"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.59,0.22,0.13,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57746"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3069"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43553"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57746"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman is admitted to the palliative care ward for end of life care. She has metastatic breast cancer with bone and liver metastases. Her other medical conditions include hypertension, osteoarthritis, Type 2 diabetes mellitus and anxiety. Her regular medications include oxycodone sustained-release and ondansetron. She reports smoking cannabis daily for the past eight months to manage pain, nausea, and poor appetite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She is agitated, sweating, and reports difficulty sleeping. She describes increased anxiety, irritability, and worsening nausea since admission 24 hours ago when she stopped using cannabis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for her cannabis withdrawal symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge for outpatient follow-up","Start diazepam","Start dronabinol","Start haloperidol","Increase oxycodone dose"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cannabis withdrawal syndrome, characterised by anxiety, irritability, sleep disturbance, and autonomic symptoms occurring within 24-48 hours of cessation. These symptoms can be particularly distressing in the palliative care setting, where symptom control is paramount.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it addresses multiple withdrawal symptoms simultaneously. Benzodiazepines can effectively manage anxiety, agitation, and insomnia associated with cannabis withdrawal. The long half-life of diazepam provides smooth coverage of symptoms and allows for gradual dose reduction as withdrawal symptoms subside.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing oxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as opioids do not specifically target withdrawal symptoms. While pain control remains important, escalating opioid doses could lead to adverse effects such as confusion or respiratory depression without addressing the underlying withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDronabinol\u003C/strong\u003E is not readily available in Australia and would essentially perpetuate cannabinoid dependence rather than address the withdrawal syndrome. Additionally, its use would complicate the assessment of other symptoms in the palliative care setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly aggressive approach to cannabis withdrawal. While it might help with nausea and agitation, its side effect profile (particularly extrapyramidal effects) makes it unsuitable as first-line therapy in this elderly patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge for outpatient follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given her palliative care needs and active withdrawal symptoms requiring close monitoring. The patient requires inpatient support for both her withdrawal symptoms and underlying palliative care needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management approach should focus on symptom control while recognising that cannabis withdrawal, though uncomfortable, is generally self-limiting over 1-2 weeks. Regular reassessment, supportive care, and adjustment of medications based on symptom severity are essential components of care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cannabis withdrawal can occur within 24-48 hours of cessation and may exacerbate symptoms in palliative care patients.","Management of cannabis withdrawal should focus on treating individual symptoms rather than using specific withdrawal protocols.","Benzodiazepines can help manage anxiety and insomnia associated with cannabis withdrawal in the palliative setting."],"references":["Herbert A, Hardy J. Medicinal cannabis use in palliative care. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2021 Jun 1;50(6):363-8. Available online at ; https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/june/medicinal-cannabis-use-in-palliative-care","Connor JP, Stjepanovi\u0107 D, Budney AJ, Le Foll B, Hall WD. Clinical management of cannabis withdrawal. Addiction. 2022 Jul;117(7):2075-95. Available online at ; https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/add.15743"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43205"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43205"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T15:52:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T15:54:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7346"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57746"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing